solution:
Given: $F=100 \mathrm{kN}=10^5 \mathrm{~N}$
$$
\begin{aligned}
& \mathrm{Y}=2 \times 10^{11} \mathrm{Nm}^{-2} \\
& \ell_0=1.0 \mathrm{~m}
\end{aligned}
$$
radius $\mathrm{r}=10 \mathrm{~mm}=10^{-2} \mathrm{~m}$
From formula, $Y=\frac{\text { Stress }}{\text { Strain }}$
$$
\Rightarrow \quad \text { Strain }=\frac{\text { Stress }}{Y}=\frac{F}{A Y}
$$
$$
\begin{aligned}
& =\frac{10^5}{\pi r^2 Y}=\frac{10^5}{3.14 \times 10^{-4} \times 2 \times 10^{11}} \\
& =\frac{1}{628}
\end{aligned}
$$
Therefore $\%$ strain $=\frac{1}{628} \times 100=0.16 \%$

Tension in the wire, $\mathrm{T}=\left(\frac{2 \mathrm{mM}}{\mathrm{m}+\mathrm{M}}\right) \mathrm{g}$
$$
\begin{aligned}
\text { Stress } &=\frac{\text { Force } / \text { Tension }}{\text { Area }}=\frac{2 \mathrm{mM}}{\mathrm{A}(\mathrm{m}+\mathrm{M})} \mathrm{g} \\
&=\frac{2(\mathrm{~m} \times 2 \mathrm{~m}) \mathrm{g}}{\mathrm{A}(\mathrm{m}+2 \mathrm{~m})}(\mathrm{M}=2 \mathrm{~m} \text { given }) \\
&=\frac{4 \mathrm{~m}^2}{3 \mathrm{~mA}} \mathrm{~g}=\frac{4 \mathrm{mg}}{3 \mathrm{~A}}
\end{aligned}
$$
